Did any of your characters die during character generation? Because that's a thing in some versions of the ruleset. You start with a character concept, roll a bunch of dice on tables for each segment of your character's career. In military careers in particular, one possible result is "ded, start over."

You can certainly adapt the setting to other rulesets. There's an official GURPS conversion, for example, though without a lot of the "cinematic" rules it's going to be really, really deadly. Player characters are going to get reduced to chunky salsa by micrometeorite impacts or stray X-ray laser beams on a regular basis unless the GM dials the lethality way, way, way back to keep things more in line with the 1950s sci-fi pulp magazine adventure feeling the original authors wanted to emulate.

There's a wiki, though it's kind of incomplete and you'll find "TBD" pages around 99% of the time when you try to drill down. There's also a page called "Freelance Traveller" that has a lot of material, including fiction set in the setting. I don't think any human character boinks a female Vargr, though.

And they aren't cute awoos in this setting, though of course a GM can decide that they are. Canonically they're small and a bit fragile and have very little sexual dimorphism--that's visible to humans, anyway, they can certainly tell one another apart. They are described as looking more like hunched-over feral wolves with slightly bigger heads, that decided momentarily to walk upright, and have pawlike hands with paw pads--and all of their body language and facial expressions are very easy to read if you've ever been around dogs. Vargr are, finally, alien. They're highly intelligent and excellent at abstract reasoning and solving problems. They're very competent scientists, mathematicians, and engineers. They think just as well as humans do, but they don't think like humans, at all.

But here. Have a qt awoo. She's awooing. Would you woo her?

This was Mongoose Traveller, so no. But one of them did get injured, which would have been a kill in earlier versions. We also rolled characters for shits and giggles, and the one I rolled was a classic example: Bad luck on his last 4 years.

I suppose lack of resources was another thing that hampered the whole thing. You basically have scanned rulebooks and whatever someone decided to throw onto some ancient-looking site. So you don't find a good, comprehensive list of rules, but you do find an amazingly detailed galactic map. But I'm not particularly interested in the setting. There's some good stuff in the splat books that brings it too life a little, but the whole far future, barely recognizable humanity weirdly trucking around with a 1970's concept of future technology just doesn't particularly speak to the imagination. The original rules seem quite geared to just making up your own stuff, though. That also extends to the aliens, which seem old-fashioned. The Vargr are kind of cool because they're heavily implied to be offshoots of dogs taken from Earth during the Stone Age, but the rest... eh. I can leave 'em. And I actually love space cats as a trope.

Another thing that really killed it for my players was the emphasis on space accounting. Most parties are going to be asking questions when the rules put such an emphasis on debt. But the central ideas of Traveller, like the character creation, fast and deadly combat, small crew space shenanigans, etc. are all quite neat.

Ah, Mongoose Traveller. Their Vargr are much more human, much less bestial, than in the GDW version. I can't find it now, but in some official art, Vargr females have bewbies, though usually they're drawn with four of them instead of two, and at least one of them looked an awful lot like Florence Ambrose, but with tits. Four tits, but tits nonetheless.

And yeah, it's an intellectual property going back to the 1970s RPG boom. It's not as popular as it used to be. There has been official material from several different companies as the property rights keep getting sold, and there are enormous contradictions between one and the next. There was a lot of material, but some's been lost, and what remains is scattered around, a lot of it on web pages last updated 20+ years ago, that still have the little "Under Construction" animated man with shovel .gif at the bottom of the page. It's frustrating, but you do have the option of picking and choosing. https://freelancetraveller.com/features/othroads/index.html has information about campaigns where they did just that.

All that having been said, the official Deep Lore of the setting is that about a third of a million years ago, a super-advanced alien race, "the Ancients," appeared, and did a lot of wild stuff. They genetically engineered creatures and put them on many worlds, they terraformed many planets--or, rather, remade them to their tastes, which didn't necessarily line up with human preferences. The Vargr were a creation of the Ancients, genetically engineered from Earthly wolves and plopped down on a somewhat Earthlike planet a couple thousand light years closer to the galactic core, and left there. No one knows why. Deepest Lore is that the Vargr were an experiment, one of many, done by aliens all but godlike in their power and technological prowess, who also created ringworlds and Dyson spheres on a whim, or as experiments, with motivations that do not quite map to anything humanly comprehensible.

>divide
You mean the variety. Everyone has a different idea of how anthros should be relative to humans. I'll use awoos as an example. This can include:
>dietary preferences (wifwolf can't eat chocolate)
>cultural differences (wolf tribes may prioritize loyalty to a legalist fault. And pack mentality, that's a big one.)
>physical differences (Is your awoo more like a kemono? How bulky is her snout? Digi-legs? Is the species larger or smaller on average?)
>Xeno-style differences (if awoos live on other planets, then their lifestyles may be more jarring than a mere cultural change)
>Language (does your wolf have an accent because of her different facial structure? Is there a language barrier?)
>Evolutionary divergence. (Did anthro wolves evolve from wolves millions of years ago? Or was the common ancestor closer to us, as if anthro wolves are primates that got fuzzier and snoot-ier from their environment. Do we just ignore this in the story, or is the evolutionary history significant?)
>"biological desires/functionality" (like if wifwolves go into heat, or if they tend to want several kids, or if they produce a litter instead of one child. Can she even reproduce with a human? Are wolves biologically inclined to have certain personality traits?)

That's just a start. You can make any of these traits as apparent or invisible as you want.
